4. Image quality checks

Implement these checks:

4.1 Missing/corrupt image detection
- Check file exists.
- Check readable by PIL/OpenCV.
- Flag unreadable files as high severity.

4.2 Dimension consistency
- Record width/height distribution.
- Flag extreme outliers.
- Flag if image/mask dimensions mismatch.

4.3 Brightness
- Compute mean grayscale intensity.
- Flag very dark images.
- Flag overexposed images.

4.4 Contrast
- Compute standard deviation of grayscale intensity.
- Flag low-contrast images.

4.5 Blur
- Compute Laplacian variance.
- Flag low blur score.

4.6 Color/channel consistency
- Detect grayscale/RGB/RGBA inconsistencies.
- Flag unexpected channel formats.

4.7 Outlier images
- Compute simple feature vector:
  - mean RGB
  - std RGB
  - brightness
  - contrast
  - blur score
  - saturation mean
- Use IsolationForest or z-score rule to flag outliers.

ImageQualityResult:
{
  "sample_id": "frame_0001.png",
  "width": 854,
  "height": 480,
  "channels": 3,
  "brightness": 112.4,
  "contrast": 44.1,
  "blur_score": 83.2,
  "is_dark": false,
  "is_overexposed": false,
  "is_low_contrast": false,
  "is_blurry": true,
  "is_outlier": false
}

5. Mask quality checks

Implement these checks:

5.1 Missing/corrupt masks
- Check each image has corresponding mask.
- Check mask is readable.
- Missing mask = high severity.

5.2 Image/mask mismatch
- Check dimensions match.
- Mismatch = high severity.

5.3 Invalid class IDs
- If class map exists, verify mask values are valid.
- Invalid class IDs = critical or high severity depending quantity.

5.4 Empty masks
- Detect masks with no foreground classes.
- Severity depends on expected dataset type.

5.5 Tiny masks
- Compute mask area per class.
- Flag objects with area below threshold.
- For multi-class masks, track per-class pixel counts.

5.6 Fragmented masks
- Use connected components per class.
- Flag unusually fragmented annotations.

5.7 Suspicious identical masks
- Hash masks.
- Flag repeated identical masks across many images.

MaskQualityResult:
{
  "sample_id": "frame_0001.png",
  "mask_path": "/path/mask.png",
  "valid": true,
  "width": 854,
  "height": 480,
  "unique_class_ids": [0,1,2,3],
  "invalid_class_ids": [],
  "empty": false,
  "foreground_ratio": 0.32,
  "num_connected_components": 14,
  "class_pixel_counts": {
    "0": 240000,
    "1": 33000,
    "2": 42000
  }
}

6. Class balance checks

Implement:

6.1 Global class distribution
- Pixel count per class.
- Image presence count per class.
- Foreground ratio per class.

6.2 Split-level class distribution
- Compare train/val/test class distributions.
- Flag rare classes missing from validation or test.
- Flag severe imbalance.

6.3 Per-video/per-source class distribution if metadata exists
- Group by video_id/source_id/patient_id if available.
- Flag classes isolated to a tiny number of sources.

ClassBalanceResult:
{
  "class_id": "2",
  "class_name": "gallbladder",
  "total_pixels": 1234567,
  "image_presence_count": 892,
  "train_presence": 701,
  "val_presence": 91,
  "test_presence": 100,
  "imbalance_warning": false
}

7. Leakage detection

Implement these leakage checks:

7.1 Exact duplicate detection
- Compute MD5 or SHA256 for image bytes.
- Flag exact duplicate images.

7.2 Near-duplicate detection
- Compute perceptual hash using imagehash.
- Find image pairs with low Hamming distance.
- Especially flag if duplicates cross train/val/test splits.

7.3 Mask duplicate detection
- Hash masks.
- Flag identical masks repeated across many samples.

7.4 Metadata leakage
If metadata.csv contains any of these columns:
- patient_id
- video_id
- case_id
- source_id
- hospital_id
- device_id

Then:
- Check whether same group appears across train and test.
- Flag group leakage as high severity.

7.5 Temporal/frame leakage
If filenames include frame numbers or video IDs:
- Infer possible video groups from filename patterns.
- Warn if frames from same inferred group appear across train/test.

LeakageCluster:
{
  "cluster_id": "cluster_001",
  "type": "near_duplicate" | "exact_duplicate" | "metadata_group_leakage",
  "severity": "high",
  "samples": [
    {
      "sample_id": "video01_frame0001.png",
      "split": "train",
      "path": "/path/image1.png"
    },
    {
      "sample_id": "video01_frame0002.png",
      "split": "test",
      "path": "/path/image2.png"
    }
  ],
  "evidence": {
    "hash_distance": 2,
    "similarity_estimate": 0.97,
    "group_key": "video01"
  },
  "recommendation": "Use video-level or patient-level splitting."
}

8. Domain shift checks

Implement lightweight domain-shift detection.

8.1 Handcrafted feature distribution
For each image, compute:
- mean RGB
- std RGB
- brightness
- contrast
- saturation
- blur score
- foreground ratio
- image dimensions
- class presence vector if mask exists

8.2 Split comparison
Compare train vs val vs test:
- brightness distribution
- contrast distribution
- blur distribution
- foreground ratio distribution
- class presence distribution

Use:
- summary stats
- Wasserstein distance if scipy available, otherwise simple mean/std deltas
- KL/JS divergence for class distribution if easy

8.3 Embedding projection
Create 2D projection using PCA from handcrafted features.
Optional: support CLIP embeddings later, but not required for MVP.

DriftResult:
{
  "feature": "brightness",
  "train_mean": 113.2,
  "test_mean": 82.4,
  "delta": 30.8,
  "severity": "medium",
  "recommendation": "Inspect whether test split contains darker frames or different video sources."
}

